**Water**

The Samana can be paddled at any flow. During floods it becomes an impressive big-big-huge-volume run! In dry season it''s a beautifl river with transparent water and nice rapids.

Most likely the river will suffer from the dam construction soon.

**The run**

You will get your wake up call just at the put in - there are few very nice and pushy class III+ rapids. There is a lot of flat water after that. The whole section is in a spectacular steep gorge full of tropical vegetation on the river banks. Pure jungle adventure!

There are around 3 solid class IV rapids on this section. Some of them definitely require scouting. When you see the big Guatape river trapped into pipes rushing into Samana from the left - it''s time to get out if you don''t want to paddle the following class IV-V gorge.

**Access**

The _put in_ is at the main highway bridge over Samana.

The usual _take out_ is the bridge called "Narices". If you are ok with class V just go down and paddle the [short canyon](http://wwater.tk/sections/uX7So2repSb84mRwD). This canyon just after the confluence with Guatape river is significantly harder and you can take out just at the confluence if you don''t want to paddle it. Actually it''s not a normal confluence it''s a huge artificial water release into Samana. There is a road going to that place but it''s locked. Try to ask someone to open it for you.

The shuttle from the put in to the take out takes around 5 hours and the road to the take out might be really bad after rains and hardly doable with a normal car.

**Note:** This section is at really low altitude. Beware of mosquito bites!!

_Mike Krutyansky, 2016_

  ', '', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.142037+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.142037+00');

На реке четыре больших порога, все едется сходу, кроме огромных волн там все равно ничего нет. Вода теплая, по берегам попадаются симпатичные туристки в бикини. Ущелье реки весьма симпатичное. Много волн для серфинга.', '', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.162773+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.162773+00');

**Water**

The river should have at least 5 cumecs at the put in after the small dam which derivates some water. There is no upper limit for this section.

This river looses water relatively slow and you can paddle it 4-5 days after the rain.

Don''t come here for scenary

_Note:_ You can go on paddling after the take out some flat water and artificial weirs and paddle also the [lower gorge](/sections/WvzwsbFiz9cW3Esqp/).

_2017_', 'After rain', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.169657+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.169657+00');

Low level: no garanty your boat coming in a good shape after passing Infiernito.

High level: extra caution is required in Infernito

To check the water level go to Malecon area (where most of rafting companies are) and ask them. You can also call to Exploradores Colombia. +57 304 670 0025 (what''s app)

**The run**

After few kilometers from the put in brigde you will find an exciting and good warm up rapids (grade III and III+). As soon as you just finished the rapids, either side you must go and catch an eddy before the Infernito. You will be able to see most of the first part of this steep section. Then there is a big eddy betweenthe upper and the lower section of Infernito. For addicting paddlers take out on the left once you finished and make couple more laps. 

In case of high slows I suggest take the entrace at the left side or in the middle, once get in this puzzle rapid, keep in middle and pray.

Then class 3 comercial section follows and after 10 km finally you get to San Gil where a f*cking cool beer is waitting for you.

**Access**

In San Gil you can get a public bus(located in PUENTE GRANDE, next to the La Hoja de Tabaco and go as far as you want. The ticket is 5000 pesos. You can also go to the Malecon, the area where most of the rafting companies are and ask them for a shuttle.

_Ariel Muñoz Delgado, 2017._ [Exploradores Colombia](http://exploradorescolombia.com/)', 'whole year except really dry periods', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.178143+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.178143+00');

The river is incredibly powerfull and big. BIG. You can serf and boof not only numerous gigantic waves but even turbulences and whirlpools :) It''s very likely that it''s the biggest river you have ever paddled.

There are not that many rapids though and they are fairly easy. Everything can be done without scouting. But don''t hurry up! The scenary is breathtaking. The section starts in the open valley with absolutely flat river. After first hour of paddling the banks become steeper and the current faster. There is not much vegetaion in the valley - on the contrary to [Samana](/rivers/95PjdgnnaxZLoEAe7) which is not that far and at the same altitude.

The further you paddle the steeper and more spectacular the banks become.

**The access**

The _put in_ is next to the historical city called Santa Fe de Antioquia. It''s worth a visit!

If you want to avoid the first kilometers of flat water you can drive the road down on the right side of the river.

The _take out_ is in the area that was recently controlled by guerillas and it''s considered as a dangerous zone. The situation is changing very fast so be sure to ask locals before you commit to this run.

Both roads to the put in and take out are in perfect conditions but it still takes a very long time to shuttle.

**_Note:_** The river is very dirty. There are a lot of cities and plants upstream. Try not to swallow the water.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'All year around', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.186049+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.186049+00');

Access: It''s possible to get to the put in with a usual car despite the dirt road

_Marcos Lage Domínguez, 2017_', 'After heavy rain', 'During a rainfall or 1-2 days after', '2018-03-24 15:12:50.559861+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:50.559861+00');

The Veo river could be one of the famous Norwegian highlights if there was no dam. Veo is fed by snow and glaciers but usually there is not enough water to paddle it even in the high season. There is no online gauge on Veo so the best advice would be just drive over the take out bridge and see if the dam releases enough water. [This is](/public/eL7XPhB2W6dsYwSJf.jpg) how it looks from the bridge when it''s low but already good for paddling. It might happen when the area is really high and the [gauge](/gauges/972seu2xBAKdLZpnZ) downstream at Sjoa river shows around 150 cumecs,

**Access**

The gorge you are going to paddle is really remote and there is even no road in the Veo valley all the way up to put in. When you drive up park as soon as you can see the river from the car and just carry your boats to the river downhill. Shallow flat water upstream is really not nice to paddle!

**The run**

Plan plenty of time. You will start from very anoying class II with very sharp rocks. It might feel too low but no worries you will enter the gorge soon. The rapids will become steeper and steeper and the river will narrow. With a lot of water this sharp boulder garden part in the canyon is the most demanding.

Then the river will change the style to bedrock. This part starts from an easy portage of a short and low canyon. Some parts of this portage can be paddled at certain flows. Here you will find a foot bridge. After that the bedrock fun starts - not that easy and fair! At this part you will be happy to have a low flow.

The bedrock fun comes to the end at some point and you start paddling continious class III-IV. Be carefull at the take out! You can scout the last paddleable and unpaddleable drops from the bridge of the main road and another bridge just a bit upstream.

Note: This valley has all the mosquitoes of Norway!

_Mike Krutyansky, 2015_', 'Heavy warm rains', 'It''s hard to find water in the river because of a dam', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.194979+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.194979+00');

This section of San Juan is a dream for any class IV kayaker. Endless fair rapids that don''t really require scouting but already are steep enough to practice boofing every 10-20 meters! They might change a bit but in 2016 there was only one landslide rapid slightly above grade IV just at the end of the section.

Some sections are really long and continuous.

The further you paddle the steeper the banks are and actually you enter the canyon even before the take out. But no worries it''s really hard to miss the take out bridge which is also the put in for the [canyon section](/sections/ojkThMJXLpJ5GqZcP/).

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_

  ', 'When the area is medium or high', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.202708+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.202708+00');

**About the river**

Louredo is a special river. It''s born at a big plateau so it stays with water for a long time after rain. It has 4-5 stars whitewater from 900 meters above sea level all the way to the confluence with Tamega at 150 meters just except a big portage between the Genesis and the Upper sections. It''s a must visit river for any class IV-V kayaker. It will be dammed soon.

**Water**

Upper Louredo is possible to paddle 3-7 days after a heavy rain. For the medium level the trees at the put in on the left bank between the weir and the bridge should be around 10 sm out of the water. 4-6 cumecs is a good level. With more water the rapids become better but the pools are too small. When the [Lower Louredo](/sections/j8kq5kuMK2nbyuNhb/) is a bit too low to be perfect it''s a good time to run Upper.

**The run**

The section starts with some flat water but steep and blocked rapids will follow soon. There are some tricky lines, holes and narrow passages. So be ready to scout a lot. The more you paddle the steeper river becomes. The crux part is a combination of a double drop followed by a good pool and then 6 meters cleen drop and a big slide after another short pool. The pool after the slide flows quite fast to the following class VI waterfall. This waterfall has been run successfully but normally it''s a portage. The pool of this waterfall is blocked by a river-wide syphon.

After the portage of this syphon there are few nice rapids and then another nasty rapid without clean lines. Portage or pin. The rest of the run is fair but not very clean. There are numerous artificial high and bony weirs until you reach the take out.

This section will take you a lot of time and energy but if you still want to paddle go on and do the [Lower](/sections/j8kq5kuMK2nbyuNhb/) - easier, cleaner and no portages (if the water level is not too low).

_Note:_ Following the dirt road to the put in just around 1 kilometer before the put in you will see a water channel on the right from the road. If you follow this water channel with boats you will arrive to a nice addition for the run - a class V long and technical rapid.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'Often in winter', '3-7 days after rainfall. 4-6 cumecs', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.210053+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.210053+00');

The gorge is virtualy inescapable with exception of couple places where you can possibly do a long hike out.

At medium water level there are actually not that many class V rapids but it makes sense to rate the entire multiday run as class V. Also the last day of paddling is not really 5 stars but the whole run is definitely 5 stars.

**The run**

The gradient starts almost immediately. On the first kilometers you will enjoy continious technical steep and already quite demanding boof paradise with enough eddies... if you are lucky with the water level. Class IV+ to V-.

After about 2 hours of paddling from the put in the style of the river changes. It enters very high canyon with sometimes absolutely steep walls. But don''t be scared. All harder rapids are easy to scout and to portage. Suddenly some sweet bedrock rapids appear. At some point there is a huge boulder blocking the entrace to the canyoun with an overhanging right wall. Almost all the river flows under this boulder - portage.

The river gets more and more spectacular with sometimes absolutel red rocks.

After the canyon opens up there will be some flat water to paddle and signes of civilization on the river banks. There is a possibility here for an emergency exit.

Then some rapids begin. The quality of these rapids are much lower than the rapids in the first canyons. They are formed by landslides.

Then the river enters the second big canyon - as spectacular as the first one but with completely different character. The rapids are made of house-size boulders and many of them are sifons. Paddle with caution because soon you will reach an unpaddleable section. Portage left or right takes around 1 hour.

After the portage the river slowly flatterns. You enjoy class III-IV paddling in a breathtaking scenary with waterfalls comming from both sides of the canyon. From the portage it''s around 2 hours to the suspension bridge. It is an option for the take out if your car can drive there. If not you can paddle to the confluence with rio Cubugon and then carry your boats for around 600 meters upstream on the right bank. There you will find a small gravel road passable with a normal car that comes to the river bank.

**_Note:_** Locals say that the whole area around Cubara down to Tame is dangerous especialy at night time due to the crimes like extortion and kidnapping committed by Venezuelans', '', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.217912+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.217912+00');

