_Mike Krutyansky, 2015_', 'After rain', 'The gauge is after the confluence with the river Furelos', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.249212+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.249212+00');

**About the river**

Rio Cabreiro is in the shade of its brothers like upper Vez and Azere and it has probably been paddled only twice to this moment. And it''s unfair for such a pure gem of Portuguese whitewater rivers. This run is much better than Azere and the same good as upper Vez but longer and a bit less steep.

**Water**

The river rises and drops fast so be ready that the water level can change while you are paddling. Don''t put in if it''s raining hard even if the level seems low.

The good flow is 4-8 cumecs. Most likely 10-12 cumecs is also good for all sections except the tripple drop combo.

The river is good 1-2 days after a heavy rainfall or during the periods of moderate-light rains. Usually it''s the same time when upper Vez and Azere are also good.

**The run**

Everything is possible to scout but there are couple class IV must-runs. There is only one potentialy hard portage of the tripple drop in a canyon but at normal water level it''s runnable with no problem. Plan the whole day for this trip. You can also start from the alternative put in 1 km downstream but you will miss some nice whitewater then.

The run starts with easy read and run rapids class III-IV.

Soon you reach the first class V rapid - it''s a steep S-bend with a dangerous towback at the end. No shame to portage or to set up a proper safety here.

After few other rapids you enter the first canyon. It''s not easy to scout some parts of it but it''s all runnable and the lines are not hard.

The rapids become cleaner and more fun and even a small portage on the left (or a chicken line at higher flows) of a big unnranable drop doesn''t spoil the fun.

After some nice rapids ypu finally reach the waterfall combo in a super narrow canyon. It looks like narrow gates to nowhere from the river level and it''s impossible to miss. Scout and portage if necessary on the right.

After the waterfalls and all the way to the take there are numerous class IV-V- clean and not so clean drops that are all easy to scout and to portage.

_Note:_ There must be some steep stuff upstream the put in.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'After rain', '1-2 days after a heavy rainfall or during the periods of moderate-light rains. 5-15 cumecs', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.258365+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.258365+00');

**Water**

Usually this section is paddled at low flows. The normal level is 2-4 cumecs which usually happens 3-7 days after a heavy rainfall. But Cavado can also be paddled with much more water. The overall grade will become something like class V.

**The run**

This description is based on "low" water which is 2-5 cumecs. Everything is easy to scout and to portage.

The run starts with some not nice boulder garden rapids. At low flows some of them can be portages.

After that you reach the main part of the run, the bedrock paradise. After few small slides there is a class VI big slide that ends with a slot. Easy portage on the left. After that thre is a serie of very nice slides of different shapes. The granite rock is very smooth and this is what makes this section so famous. Very soon you reach a technical 4-meters drop (class V) with a dangerous cave on the right. Must boof. Few more nice slides bring you to the end of the bedrock section and the start of nasty boulder garden rapids with some minor syphons and undercuts.

At normal flow the grade doesn''t go above IV except for the portage and the 4-meter drop.

**Access**

_Put in:_ Park at the beginning of the dirt road and if the first 100 meters of this road is ok for your car you can drive down. If the water level is low or medium then drive straight at the first intersection and go the point on the map called "Low water put in". By doing this you will avoid lowering you boats down with rope and nasty low water boulder garden paddling.

_Note:_ The run is short but the shuttle is long

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'After rain', 'The normal level is 2-4 cumecs which usually happens 3-7 days after a heavy rainfall. But Cavado can also be paddled with much more water. The overall grade will become something like class V.', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.268683+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.268683+00');

If the level is really high (500 cumecs) there is only flat but fast water.', 'All winter', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.276452+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.276452+00');

It''s your last option to paddle in the region when there is no rain before you head to the sea. Because of few ideal surfing waves and someties holes it can be even interesting for some class IV-V paddlers.

There is an online gauge downstream at Salvaterra but it takes the river few hours to flow from the section to the gauge. They also often open and close the dam during the day causing very significant level changes so don''t rely on this gauge. The thing is that for this section the less water is the better. At 60 cumecs (Salvaterra gauge) there are few really nice waves to surf. They are very stable with no pulsation with easy entraces. At high flows of few hundred cumecs the river flatterns and there is nothing interesting except powerfull turbulence. Don''t even bother. It can also become quite dangerous for class II kayakers without a good escimo roll at these flows.

At low flows (around 40 cumecs) there are some small drops, eddie lines and couple small waves to surf. There is enough completely flat water at low flows.

Be carefull with iron in the river and some minor syphons in the artificial structures close to the banks.

The scenary is actually quite nice especially at low flows when the low canyon after the bridge is not under the water.

**Access**

The take is hard to recognise from water so scout it first. The dirt road to the take out might be tricky for some cars and vans in particular so scout the road too. If you don''t want to drive this dirt road you can paddle a bit further and take out at the Sela train station. There is only flat water and really beautiful rock formations on the river banks down to Sela.

_Mike Krutynasky, 2016_', 'Always', 'The less water the more fun! Dam release', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.445031+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.445031+00');

Oitaven is one of the best class IV-V runs in the whole region. It starts from a huge dam and this dam always releases a certain amount of water. The flow doesn''t change naturally. It can stay for days at certain level and then drop significantly within one hour. So just before paddling go online and check the flow and have a backup plan in case of a sudden closure or release of the damn. Usually they will reduce flow if it doesn''t rain and release the water during or just after the rain. It''s unlikely to see an unexpected water release from this damn.

**The run**

With right flow there are no portages and very little flat water. You can start to enjoy Oitaven from 4 cumecs but with this little water you will have to portage few rapids. Around 14 cumecs is probably the ideal flow - no need to portage anything and all the rapids are quite fair. At this flow you will face a very short but must-run class V canyon in the beginning. With much more water this part would probably become too dangerous that''s why we have defined 16 cumecs as the upper limit.

After this short canyon everything is scoutable and portageable and the eddies between the rapids are mostly big enough. The further you paddle the cleaner river becomes and at some point you will start enjoying bedrock rapids. The crux rapid in this part is a long slide with a big but manageable hole at the end. Few more nice slides bring you to a spectacular and clean double drop

After this drop the rapids become easier and very soon all the fun is over.

If there is too much water you can paddle just the part after the drop. There is a dirt road to the river but it''s not easy to find.

