It''s quite a demanding run. You don''t want to run it with too much water! [This pictire](http://wwater.tk/public/rW9uD4jcexdwDjrxA.jpg) is taken from the put in bridge downstream at high but not the highest possible flow. It''s strongly not recommended to run the canyon for the first time with more water than this.

For the first time plan the whole day for the run especially with higher flows. Scouting and portaging is often hard especially in the beginning after the portage. There are lot of must runs.

In 2016 there was a portage (class VI) in the first part of the canyon before the suspension bridge.

There is a big chance you will like to repeat the run and it''s a lot of fun!

_Note:_ It''s a good idea to paddle couple kilometers more especially at high flow. There are some nice class IV rapids for relief.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'Medium water levels in the area', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.56745+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.56745+00');

This section of Bestança is nice if you are lucky with the flow. It shouldn''t be too high and if it''s low it gets really bony and not nice. If it looks like 7-15 cumecs then it''s fine. With low flow it''s clss IV with syphons portages. With 15 cumecs it''s class IV+ with some V and portages.

**The run**

Everything is easy to scout and portage. Plan the whole day for the run. It will take you 4 or more hours. There are no remarkable highlights but the run is quite technical and fun. There is no proper road following the river but it''s always possible to escape in case of need.

After 40 minutes of class IV boulder garden you reach the entrance to the first small gorge. After few runnable class IV+ drops in this gorge there is a big 30 minutes portage of the waterfall in two channels. The right channel is waiting for a hero.

Then the river goes down really steep. There are some drops and a lot of boulder garden rapids. A lot to scout and maybe some stuff to portage depending on the water level.

Closer to the end there is another low canyon with some really nice bedrock rapids and one mandatory portage.

**The scenary** is not really spectacular but the river flows through the forest even at steep sections which makes it look special.

**Access**

The put in is a very beautiful roman bridge called "Ponte de Covelas". There is a wide path from the parking to the bridge and a touristic sign post at the parking. It''s an easy 10-15 walk downhill. Just stay on the widest trail while going down.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'After rain', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.574052+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.574052+00');

The water is diverted by the dam for the whole run. The dam is 1 km after the put in and it takes roughly 20 cumecs but they can suddenly close it or open while you are running the river. The optimum amount is around 15-25 cumecs after the dam. Above 30 the section becomes much more demanding. Don''t go into the gorge if it feels like more than 30 cumecs after the dam and it''s your first time on the river.

You can get an idea about the water level at the put in bridge and ask locals there. Average or slightly above average should be good but you will never know exactly before you reach the dam.

When the area is high the dam can actually help you - otherwise the gorge of Calderas would be too high.

**The run**

It''s hands down 5 stars run. The section consists of endless technical drops not all of them are fair. It''s kind of a boulder garden pool-drop style. 

The crux part is quite long, very steep and require a lot of scouting. Horizon lines makes you feel like a portage is coming but as soon as you start scouting you find out that there are always cleen and fun lines! Still probably you will be happy to portage some drops. Everything is scoutable and portagable.

The dam in the beginning is also runnable and the pool after it is deep enough. You can scout it from the right using a small underwater step just at the edge.

It''s defenitely worth to paddle it again and then one more time and then again! The first time it will take you the whole day but then you can do it within 1 hour.

**Access**

The put in is on the main highway. The road to the take out is new and good. It''s a dirt road but doable with no problems with a normal car or van. Take out on the left bank just after the water release from the power station and use a small path to go up.

Alternatively you can paddle for 2 hours class III-IV with a lot of flats all the way down to the Samana bridge.

_Note:_ The resolution of sattelite images from google for this section are excellent!

