Расход реки регулируется дамбой, от которой вы начнете сплав. Режим ее работы - загадка, так что присутствует элемент лотереи. Однако, шанс, что воды совсем не будет, ничтожно мал. Обычно расход реки резко увеличивается в районе 11-12 часов дня. Однако, существенного влияния на сложность реки это не оказывает.

Багирати быстро течет внутри глубокого и красивого ущелья почти без участков стоячей воды. Множество идеальных катальных волн с перезаходом. Примерно посередине секции расположен порог, который стоит посмотреть. Ориентиры - слепой правый поворот реки в каньоне. Надо зачалиться на левый берег. Второй порог, который лучше посмотреть, расположен непосредственно в Девпраяге недалеко от слияния. Ориентиры - два автомобильных моста и ступени гхатов на левом берегу. Порог очень интересный.', '', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.585858+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.585858+00');

**Water**

You can paddle this section almost any day in winter and it is what makes this section so special. It''s also one of the closest sections to Porto. You can paddle this section at super low flows when it hasn''t been raining for 2 weeks and then it''s class IV with one rapid class V. You can also paddle it at super high flows after heavy rains and then it''s class IV+ to V.

The range is like 8 - 150 cumecs.

There is a gauge just upstream the bridge of the put in. 3.30 is kind of a low limit.

**The run**

It''s rapid - pool style even at very high flows. Everything is easy to scout and portage. There is a sightseeing wooden path on the left bank through the whole gorge. In the middle of the run there is a road comming down to the Vau beach on the left. It''s a good point to start if you have doubts about running the whole section. The run is not very clean at low water but it''s still good. At low water be carefull with minor syphons and pin spots

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'All winter', '1-25 days after rainfall. Basicly paddleable all winter with almost any water level', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.591877+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.591877+00');

**About the river**

Louredo is a special river. It''s born at a big plateau so it stays with water for a long time after rain. It has 4-5 stars whitewater from 900 meters above sea level all the way to the confluence with Tamega at 150 meters just except a big portage between the Genesis and the Upper sections. It''s a must visit river for any class IV-V kayaker. It will be dammed soon.

**Water**

The good level is 4-7 cumecs

The optimum level is when the trees on the left bank at the put in of the lower section are just at the water level or a little bit awashed.

With low water it''s too bony but a lot of stuff is still runable. The river is too steep to be runnable with too much water.

It''s good for 2-4 days after a heavy rain.

**The run**

It''s probably the highest ru nin Portugal (above the sea level).

Part of the run can be seen from the road while driving to the put in but there is no real need to scout it in advance if you are certain about the water flow. Everything is possible to scout and to portage.

The run starts in the open valley with not much vegetation. There are some grade IV slides and most of them are doable without getting out of the boat but there also couple class V-VI rapids.

At some point there is a boulder garden section which is basicly some scratching and some portaging.

After the small tributary from the right the river flows in a low canyon with nice steep rapids and cool boofs and maybe some portages depending on the flow.

_Note 1:_ Although the road seems to be following the river on the map it''s quite far above.

_Note2:_ **** Between this section and the [next one](/sections/8zCgSTmDY8ZPuuTxq/) there is some flat water, few rapids and a huge portage

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'After rain', '2-4 days after rainfall. 4-7 cumecs', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.59842+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.59842+00');

The start of the short lower canyon is the artificial confluence with the Guatape river. It''s a pure big volume run in a narrow canyon. At high flows there are only waves but the waves are huge! As you paddle down the canyon becomes more and more narrow and the crux part of it is hard to scout. The crux is a left bend and the water is pushing hard against the right wall. Just stay left! After this bend there is a small and short easier rapid and the canyon opens up. 

**Access**

It''s not a good idea to paddle just this short stretch. Start at Samana bridge and paddle [the classic](http://wwater.tk/sections/2QYbd5xGPAvrSLwt8)! And then if you really liked the last canyon you can do it again. For that find a road to the water release station and try to find somebody who can open you the gate.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2016_', '', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.604536+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.604536+00');

At low flows the run is a nice technical class V section. The rapids change very often and there are a lot of trees in the river so paddle with caution! Be careful of landslides on rainy days. At higher flows the secton is extremely demanding and it can become class VI or unpaddleable.

**The water**

It''s a low water run. The section is paddleable when the glacier melt is not strong - early spring or autumn. You can estimate the water level at the take out. If the rapids upstream look paddleable and there are enough eddies to stop before the section that ends with a huge river-wide syphon.

