It''s one of the best runs in Portugal if not the best. A lot of powerfull rapids with pools in between with some bigvolume stuff at the end.

**Water**

There should be 15-40 cumecs at the put in. The easy rapid just after the bridge should look like grade III+ and it should be passable with not much scratching. The river is runnable 3-7 days after a heavy rainfall. It would be runnable much longer if not a dam above with a derivation pipe. The water diverts to Tamega.

**The run**

It starts with easy class III-IV. Then the river narrows and picks up its pace. After few class IV-V rapids you reach the crux. It''s a big and steep 3-steps rapid. Be careful, there are some big syphons. Scout and portage if necessary on the left.

After the crux there are numerous class IV-V powerfull rapids. Many of them are read and run but some require scouting.

At last you arrive the confluence with Tamega and then there are 3 big volume rapids with fairly easy lines. Scout from the right. Be very carefull when you see industrial works on the banks. They are building a dam and changing the river bed.

After the last rapid there is around 10 minutes of flat water with artificial weirs. You can drive the dirt road on the right to reduce the amount of flat water.

_Note: If you remember all the lines and don''t have to portage anything the run is doable in 1 hour._', 'After rain', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.636694+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.636694+00');

After a short warm up you suddenly enter the canyon. Take out on the left and scout the first rapid. The second one is quite steep. It comes shortly after the pool and it can also be easily scouted from the left. The rest of the canyon is easier but at medium flows there is a river-wide hole.

The most difficult rapid (V- at some flows) is just before the road bridge. It''s well visiable from the bridge but better to scout it from the river from the right bank.

Don''t take out at this bridge! There are 2 minor rapids downstream and one nice boof with a tricky approach in the right channel just before the power plant building on the river left.

**Take out:** You should get off the main road and cross the river by an old narrow bridge from right bank to the left. drive the dirt road on the river left downstream for around 500 meters to the end of the road which is a small power station.

Note 1: Do it 1-2-3 times in a row! The distance for shuttling is so short that you can just run it.

Note 2: There is a service area for camper vans at the put in free of charge. You can sleep in your van there, refill water and drain waste water.

Note 3: If the water level is above 20 cumecs you can put in a bit upstream and paddle class III down to the put-in bridge

_Mike Krutyansky, 2015_', 'Often in winter', '1-10 days after rainfall', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.645745+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.645745+00');

This run is too short to drive all the way to here but honestly how often did you have dreams of chilling out in hot springs after few days of kayaking non-stop in winter? So here we are - just 1 km upstream the put in of lower Caldo there are termal springs free of charge! You can actually put in just at hot springs and paddle class 2 to the normal put-in.

**Water**

The river is very short and it goes up and down extremely fast. [The online gauge](http://saih.chminosil.es/index.php?url=/datos/ficha/estacion:N019/area:HID) should read approximately 4 cumecs minimum and 20 cumecs maximum. From around 10 cumecs the run is more like class IV. It''s most likely doable with much more water but scout the take out first!

**The run**

It''s read and run all the way - no real need to get out of your boat (unless you have log jams in flat sections). All the rapids are clean bedrock slides. But if you are not a very strong crew or the water level is above 10 cumecs - scout the take out eddy first!. From the take out bridge you will see big slides - you have to stop before the first (the biggest) one. It''s relatively easy to hike out using a path on the left bank.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'After rain', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.655362+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.655362+00');

**The run**

The first run requires some scouting which is always easy. It is the place to play around and try different lines! At medium-low flows the hole under the road bridge is quite sticky. At medium and high flows swimming in this section is very dangerous because of very strong turbulence. Perfect roll is the must here!

**Water**

Åmot can be run at any flow. Below 40 cumecs te run is more technical and there are more lines and features to play with. At very high flows the run becomes really emotional but still possible and technically not hard. It can be paddled even at 300 cumecs but the eddies and vertical turbulences become really insane at these flows.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'All summer', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.885699+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.885699+00');

Suarez is probably the most famous white water river in Colombia. It''s paddled quite often although the river is very demanding and most of the parts are class V. It''s world famous for being "class V big-volume multiday". The normal approach to this river is doing a 4-5 days multiday trip from Barbosa to the confluence with Chicamocha. But some folks prefer to paddle empty boats because of the difficulty of the river. Also different parts are good at different water levels. There are some easy and medium-easy approaches to the river at some places between Barbosa and the commercial section. So in this description we will divide the run into few parts.

**Water level**

There is a gauge at the put in of rafting section. You can check it out or call to Exploradores Colombia. +57 304 670 0025 (what''s app).

This section needs medium-low level.

During the dry period this section can be too low

**The run**

The rock here is very unusual - it’s very sharp and guttered and it hurts a lot if you were unlucky to swim.

The river starts from some slides that look artificial but they are not! Start getting used to the style - unlike most of the other Colombian rivers this one will surprize you with ammount of perfect shaped bedrock slides and drops.

The river flattens soon and you start paddling slow flat water.

Then the drops start. After few nice drops you reach the first portage (class VI) - portage on the left. Soon there is the second portage (class VI) - portage on the left.

After few more rapids you come to clean slides - a big volume version of Store Ula slides. Really scary if you have a lot of water! Scouting and if needed portaging on the left. Then few class IV-V rapids bring you to the bridge of the main road.

**Access**

The roads to the put in and the take out are good for all types of cars.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'All year except months with the most rain (May, October)', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.664564+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.664564+00');

**Water**

Tamega stays with water for long time without any rain. This section normally has water for the whole winter due to a lot of tributaries.This section doesn''t have the upper limit. 

**The run**

Everything is easy to scout and possible to portage at normal levels. With flood there might be some problems with portaging but there shouldn''t be anything harder than grade IV.

It starts with around 30 minutes of flat water. When you finally reach the canyon you will find few class II-III rapids with some eddy lines and options for easy training.

There is one rapid with a powerfull hole at the end at certain flows.

The hardest and the steepest rapid is just 100 meters before the take out and it''s well visiable from the bridge. You can walk upstream and scout it from the take out if you really want it.

**Access:**

The take out is a beach.

The road to the take out is a dirt road but it''s fairly good for any car all the way to the end.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_

  ', 'November-April. All winter', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.681131+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.681131+00');

**Water**

There should be 5 or more cumecs at the put in. The take out is after the confluence with the same size river Covas, a lake and a dam that derivates some water so it''s a bad place to judge the water level in this section. There is no upper limit to run this section but some places might become a bit harder with a lot of water.

The river doesn''t drain fast and it stays with water for around 7-9 days after a heavy rainfall.

**The run**

Scouting and portaging is always possible but sometimes not super easy.

The run starts from quite a long part of class II with a lot of vegetation on the banks.

After the river narrows to a gorge you will soon find the hardest rapid of this section (class IV). Be careful at low flows here and don''t forget to scout it.

There is quite a lot of flat water to start being bored but always something nice follows after the next corner. There are few gorges with nice rapids in them and some of the artificial weirs are not that bad (although the others are really anoying).

One of the weirs is a clean 3-4 meters drop perfecr for boofing, stomping and freewheling.

After the confluence with Covas there is one small and easy canyon with twice more water but then you reach an artificial lake. After some flat water training have a look at the dam and probably run it at low flows if the towback behind it doesn''t look bad. This dam derivates at least 5 cumecs.

There are just few hundred meters of easy slides with not much vertical drop from the dam to the take out bridge.

**Access**

_Alternative take out:_ If you don''t want to paddle the lake, portage or run the dam and paddle the last few hundred meters you can take out at the confluence with Covas river. There is a steep dirt road coming to the bridge which is really bad for not a 4*4 car.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'November-April', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.690777+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.690777+00');

**Water**

This run can be done at huge variety of water levels (3-12 days after a heavy rainfall). The reasonable mininum is around 10 cumecs at the take out. The run is more like IV- with enough big eddies at low flows. It''s one of the sections where you can still get some fun when Portugal is low.

At high flows the eddies are very small and it''s hard to stop. It''s IV+ then.

**The run**

Sex Up is a classic non-stop continous section with small and medium boulders as obstacles. Everything is easy to scout and to portage.

After some warm up the river starts to go down quite intense. Everything can be paddled without scouting. For the first time it''s highly recomended to stop for scouting because of minor undercuts, syphons and potential log jams. And then if you liked it.. do it all over again remembering the lines and trying to improve them!

Note: On the way to the put in you will cross the river upstream the power plant that releases water. Don''t estimate water level there!

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'November-April. All winter', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.715276+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.715276+00');

All the rest doesn''t require scouting. After you see the first buildings there is a flat section with some artificial weirs. But it''s not the end - you will still have a small canyon with couple nice class II-III rapids. Take out is on the left just before the dam building.

**Water**

You can paddle this section during the whole winter. Usually just one heavy rain in autumn is enogh to make it runnable for the rest of winter. The upper limit doesn''t exist.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'November-May. All winter', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.723634+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.723634+00');

In the first part there is the crux rapid. It’s steep, long and quite hard (V+) but it really depends on the water level. Scouting and portaging is easy on the left but be careful catching a left eddy.

Some numerous technical rapids follow. Scout and style them!', 'Whole summer', '', '2018-03-24 15:12:50.499091+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:50.499091+00');

It''s hard to get a proper water level here. 6-12 cumecs is ok. This section is often too low and during a rainfall it can be too high. It rises and drops really fast with rain. There are two rocks in the river 10 meters upstream the put in bridge. The perfect level is when they are just about to be awashed. If they are dry it''s low and if you can''t see them it''s too high. The perfect timing is 0-2 day after a rainfall or when there is a little rain.

**The run**

It’s a short run with different kinds of obstacles. There are boulder garden rapids in the beginning. Some of them are nasty while the others are really technical and nice.

Very soon you reach a class V+ - VI rapid. It’s a technical entrance with a narrow slot at the exit. Portage on the left. It’s possible to start just after the slot and before a river-wide hole that looks worse than it actually is. This section can be seen from the road on the river left.

After the portage there is a nice short canyon with a technical class IV-V drop combination. It’s possible to portage the whole canyon on the left.

At the end of the run after some fast-flowing class III there is a nasty rapid on the left bend on the river. It comes really unexpectedly but it definitely needs scouting. 100 meters after this rapid there is the take out bridge. Be careful! At high flows the whole behind the bridge is really nasty and at low flows the water goes into the syphons under the bridge.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'After rain', '1-3 days after rainfall. It needs and takes more water than upper Vez but less than middle', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.743061+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.743061+00');

Suarez is probably the most famous white water river in Colombia. It''s paddled quite often although the river is very demanding and most of the parts are class V. It''s world famous for being "class V big-volume multiday". The normal approach to this river is doing a 4-5 days multiday trip from Barbosa to the confluence with Chicamocha. But some folks prefer to paddle empty boats because of the difficulty of the river. Also different parts are good at different water levels. There are some easy and medium-easy approaches to the river at some places between Barbosa and the commercial section. So in this description we will divide the run into few parts.

