There are some portages and must-runs but the total difficulty really depends on water levels.

**Water level**

We were only the second group paddling Umrew so there is not enough observation data on water levels. It does get too high during the rainy season. But it also gets too low only 6 days after a heavy rainfall. 8 cumecs at the put it in is around minimum to paddle the river. (Put in at the bridge before the British put in) At around 25 cumecs the run will become way more demanding but more fun.

We were paddling it at the minimum water level.

It''s really hard to get an idea of the water level from the take out bridge because the river is absolutely flat and wide there. It should be definitely be above 25 cumecs there.

**Access**

It will take you around one day to reach the point where you can start paddling. The shortest hike down brings you to the wrong spot! If you choose this way you will end up portaging chaotic steep boulder syphons for 1 day or more. Try to navigate to reach the right foot bridge marked as put-in on the map here. The right hike might take you from 2 to 5 hours. It’s possible to hire porters in Wakhen village.

The problem is that if the river is too low you really don''t want to hike back to the village. If there are 3-5 cumecs it''s still worth paddling down rather than taking a steep hike back.

There are hiking trails coming down to the river quite a few times from both sides and there are also few suspension bridges. They are only emergency exits since all the roads and villages are really far. It''s quite likely to meet fishermen along the river.

**The run**

From the very beginning you recognise the character of the river. It will become only cleaner on the way down. Upstream the put in there are only unrunnable syphons and boulder piles. Depending on the water level there are couple portages just after the put in.

At low water everything is easy to scout and to portage but it will become harder when the water goes up.

Most of the rapids are boulder gardens all shapes with many small nice boofs even if there is not much water. Most of the time there are fairly big pools between the rapids.

Don''t be too upset if the water level is low. It''s an absolutely beautiful and remote trip!

The things are becoming easier around the bridge number 4 but after a big tributary coming from the right there is another gorge with couple nasty steep rapids. It will take some time to portage them.

After the bridge number 6 there is only class III to the take out.

_Tip:_ Beware of syphons and undercuts!

